<DOC><DOCNO> AP891129-0090 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-89 1158EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Burma     11-29 0331</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Burma,0344</SECOND><HEAD>Burmese Junta Meets With Political Party</HEAD><DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The military government met with anopposition political party for the first time and repeated itspledge to hold free elections in May, a party source said today.   Meanwhile, Thai authorities said Burmese government troops havelaunched their first big attack in four months on two rebel campsnear the Thai border.   A member of the opposition Union Nationals Democracy Party saidin Rangoon that Brig. Gen. Khin Nyunt, the second-rankinggovernment official, held an hour of talks Tuesday with the party'sgeneral secretary, Kyi Han.   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted KhinNyunt as saying the government has ordered officials at all levelsto be strictly neutral in the election.   The military junta came to power in a September 1988 coup inwhich soldiers killed hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators.   In recent months the junta has cracked down again on theopposition. Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, the leaders of the popularopposition National League For Democracy, were put under housearrest July 20.   Of the 206 political parties registered to take part in theelections, six have developed a national network. They include theNational League For Democracy and the Union Nationals DemocracyParty.   It was not immediately known why Khin Nyunt met only with anofficial of the Union Nationals.   In the northern Thai town of Mae Sot, a border patrol policeofficer said Burmese forces fired mortar and artillery guns at twocamps of the ethnic Karen rebels. The officer, who spoke oncondition of anonymity, said the offensive began Tuesday night justacross the border from Mae Sot.   He said 2,000 rebels were defending the camps against about4,000 government soldiers. The officer said he had no informationon casualties.   The Karens withstood a fierce government offensive in late July.   The ethnic minority is one of the strongest of a dozen guerrillagroups fighting for greater regional autonomy.</TEXT></DOC>